content.description: This is the left route on this shorter central section of wall. Some tricky slab moves on somewhat spcaed out bolts bring you to a ledge before the final body length face (crux) and the top. The final bolt is placed in a way that guarantees a nasty ledge fall if you botch the top out. Probably more fun as a TR. Shares an anchor with the route to the right.
The right of two routes on this short face. Good holds with a slab move or two for the top out. The top can be wet in the early season or after the rain.
content.protection: 5 bolts, 2 bolt chain anchor.   The first and last bolts along with the anchor are severely corroded. Do not use the older 3 bolt anchor to the right.
content.location: Right route on the lower angle face at the center of the wall.

content.description: This Route follows the right side of a prominent rounded arete. The first bolt is after a 15 ft scramble on somewhat mossy rock. A reach to a jug will get you past the first bulge (crux?). Stays mostly right of the bolt line past a couple more bulges to the top.

This area offers a handful of fun moderates with decent rock quality (for a road cut). The wall is south facing, dries quickly after the rain and will receive sun all evening. This is an older climbing area and as of 2018 many lead bolts and all of the top anchors show signs of serious corrosion. Check the bolts!  Some good looking development potential for harder projects exists in this area as well. 

  If someone has the names and FA info for this area, please update!
